  { question: "How do I calculate fuel cost for a trip in liters?", answer: "Multiply the trip distance in km by your vehicle's L/100km rating, then divide by 100 to get total liters needed. Multiply liters by the price per liter. For example, a 400 km trip at 8 L/100km needs 32 liters. At $1.50/liter, the trip costs $48." },
  { question: "How do I convert MPG to L/100km?", answer: "The formula is L/100km = 235.215 / MPG. For example, 30 MPG = 235.215 / 30 = 7.84 L/100km. Higher MPG means lower L/100km and better fuel efficiency. This calculator handles the conversion automatically when you select MPG." },
  { question: "What is a good fuel efficiency for a car?", answer: "In L/100km, 5-7 is excellent (compact and hybrid cars), 7-10 is good (midsize sedans), 10-13 is average (SUVs and larger vehicles), and above 13 is below average. In MPG, 30+ is excellent, 25-30 is good, 20-25 is average, and below 20 is poor." },
  { question: "Does driving speed affect fuel cost per trip?", answer: "Yes, significantly. Most vehicles achieve optimal fuel efficiency between 80-100 km/h (50-65 mph). At 120 km/h, fuel consumption increases by roughly 20% compared to 90 km/h due to increased aerodynamic drag. Slowing down on long trips can meaningfully reduce your fuel cost." },
  { question: "Should I calculate fuel cost for a round trip?", answer: "Yes, double the one-way distance for a round trip. Remember that return journey conditions may differ: driving into wind, elevation changes, and traffic patterns can make the return use more or less fuel than the outward journey. Adding a 5-10% buffer to your estimate accounts for these variables." }
