    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Fuel Cost Per Trip Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Planning a road trip, daily commute, or delivery route? This calculator takes the guesswork out of fuel budgeting. Unlike basic fuel cost calculators that only work with one measurement system, this tool supports metric (km, L/100km, price per liter) and imperial (miles, MPG, price per gallon) units, plus the hybrid km/L measurement common in many countries. Select the units that match your vehicle's dashboard and local fuel station, and the calculator handles all the conversions behind the scenes.
      </p>
      <p>
        Enter your trip distance, your vehicle's fuel efficiency rating, and the current fuel price. The calculator shows the total trip fuel cost, the exact amount of fuel needed in both liters and gallons, and the per-kilometer and per-mile cost breakdown. It also converts your efficiency rating to L/100km regardless of what you entered, so you always have a consistent reference point.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Fuel Cost Formulas</h2>
      <p>
        The core formula in metric is: <strong>Trip Cost = (Distance in km x L/100km / 100) x Price per Liter</strong>. When MPG is used, the calculator first converts to L/100km using: <strong>L/100km = 235.215 / MPG</strong>. For km/L, the conversion is: <strong>L/100km = 100 / km/L</strong>. All results are then derived from the total fuel needed in liters and the normalized price per liter.
      </p>

      <h3>Planning Road Trip Budgets</h3>
      <p>
        For road trips, add a 10-15% buffer to the calculated fuel cost to account for detours, traffic, stop-and-go driving in towns, and fuel price variations along the route. Mountain passes and sustained highway speeds above 110 km/h can increase consumption by 15-25% compared to the rated efficiency. If driving through multiple states or countries, fuel prices may vary significantly, so research average prices along your route for a more accurate budget.
      </p>

      <h3>Commute Cost Analysis</h3>
      <p>
        Calculate your daily commute cost, then multiply by your working days per month (typically 20-22) to see the monthly impact. This number is essential when evaluating whether a job offer with a longer commute truly pays more. It also helps you decide if switching to a more fuel-efficient vehicle, carpooling, or using public transit would save money.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate fuel cost for a trip in liters?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the trip distance in km by your vehicle's L/100km rating, then divide by 100 to get total liters needed. Multiply liters by the price per liter. For example, a 400 km trip at 8 L/100km needs 32 liters. At $1.50/liter, the trip costs $48.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert MPG to L/100km?</h3>
      <p>
        The formula is L/100km = 235.215 / MPG. For example, 30 MPG = 235.215 / 30 = 7.84 L/100km. Higher MPG means lower L/100km and better fuel efficiency. This calculator handles the conversion automatically when you select MPG.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a good fuel efficiency for a car?</h3>
      <p>
        In L/100km, 5-7 is excellent (compact and hybrid cars), 7-10 is good (midsize sedans), 10-13 is average (SUVs and larger vehicles), and above 13 is below average. In MPG, 30+ is excellent, 25-30 is good, 20-25 is average, and below 20 is poor.
      </p>

      <h3>Does driving speed affect fuel cost per trip?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, significantly. Most vehicles achieve optimal fuel efficiency between 80-100 km/h (50-65 mph). At 120 km/h, fuel consumption increases by roughly 20% compared to 90 km/h due to increased aerodynamic drag. Slowing down on long trips can meaningfully reduce your fuel cost.
      </p>

      <h3>Should I calculate fuel cost for a round trip?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, double the one-way distance for a round trip. Remember that return journey conditions may differ: driving into wind, elevation changes, and traffic patterns can make the return use more or less fuel than the outward journey. Adding a 5-10% buffer to your estimate accounts for these variables.
      </p>

